<aura:component extends="auradocs:topicPanel">

    <aura:set attribute="title" value="Value Object Types"/>

    <p>These are the most commonly used value object types. Available methods can be found via the links in the <b>Value Object</b> column.</p>

    <table class="table table-bordered table-striped">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Value Object</th>
                <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><auradocs:referenceTopicLink topic="api:SimpleValue">SimpleValue</auradocs:referenceTopicLink></td>
                <td>A value object wrapper for a primitive, such as a number, string, boolean, or date.</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><auradocs:referenceTopicLink topic="api:ArrayValue">ArrayValue</auradocs:referenceTopicLink></td>
                <td>A value object wrapper for an array. Each member of the array is a value object rather than a JavaScript literal value.</td>            
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><auradocs:referenceTopicLink topic="api:MapValue">MapValue</auradocs:referenceTopicLink></td>
                <td>A value object wrapper for a map. Each value in the map is a value object rather than a JavaScript literal value.</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
              <td><auradocs:referenceTopicLink topic="api:ActionReferenceValue">ActionReferenceValue</auradocs:referenceTopicLink></td>
                <td>ActionReferenceValue is the underlying value object for an attribute in a component of type Aura.Action. You can use <code>ActionReferenceValue</code> to pass an action to another component that will invoke the action. See <auradocs:topicLink topic="attrTypesAuraSpecific">Aura-Specific Types</auradocs:topicLink>.</td>               
            </tr>

        </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Aura also supports the <code>FunctionCallValue</code> and <code>PropertyReferenceValue</code> types. These immutable types represent constructs in the expression language. You don't need to use them as Aura evaluates them for you.</p>

</aura:component>
